text.en_US: Aren't you a \c[3]Hexacast\c[0]? How do you have that sword?!
It's from a \c[3]Triblader\c[0] skill.
But that's not your class!
You can equip moves from other classes using \c[3]custom skills\c[0].

message.en_US: Hi!
Hey there! Are you also a user of \c[3]custom skills\c[0]?
They let you equip moves from other classes.
You can mix and match, too. I've got a pretty crazy hybrid loadout equipped right now.
Just head over there, you can configure custom skills in that room.

text.en_US: Really, can I equip those too?
Of course! You can do it in the \c[3]room to the east\c[0].
Wow, that's pretty cool! You can spawn your own enemies?
It's not too complicated once you look at the game files.
Can you show me? Please?!

message.en_US: Hi!
Oh hey, Lea! I was just teaching this guy about enemy modding.
This is all really cool! Did you know that she made a modified version of those penguin things?
I want to do that myself! I can think of so many ideas I want to try!
Well, you should start by simply learning how to spawn vanilla Crossworlds enemies.
Then come on already! I want to go and show everyone!
Hold on, you can't just go spawning enemies in the official areas. You will get in trouble!
Nah, I promise it will just be between me and my friends.
Oh brother...\. This is not going to end well.

text.en_US: I can teach you, but don't go spawning enemies in the official areas.
Aww, so I can't go fight a bunch of Hedgehags in the middle of Rhombus Square?
You would get in a lot of trouble for that.
That is EXACTLY what you should not be doing.

message.en_US: Oh hey, Lea!
Hi!
Thanks a lot again for your help earlier.
Who knows what could have happened if those \v[combat.name.penguin-heat]s\c[0] escaped into the official areas.
I've been learning how to make custom NPCs.
I made these advisor NPCs and programmed them to give out random gameplay tips if you keep talking to them.
It's a good starting point but I need to figure out how to make them move around next.
Welcome!\. Here you can find helpful \i[class-hexa]\c[3]Hexacast\c[0] tips.

Tip: \i[element-heat]\c[3]Shadowflame Sorcery\c[0] can be used again while still active to skip the casting animation and immediately add a full duration's worth to the existing buff's remaining time.

Tip: The row of fire that appears while guarding during \i[element-heat]\c[3]Shadowflame Sorcery\c[0] behaves slightly different than the fire that appears during dashes. The guard flames will block light projectiles!
Tip: While \i[element-heat]\c[3]Shadowflame Sorcery\c[0] is active, \i[element-heat]\c[3]Augmented Flames\c[0] will turn into a completely different move!
Tip: Don't overlook \i[element-cold]\c[3]Brittle Barrier\c[0]! It may seem weak, but the projectile blocking effect can go a long way towards preventing your actions from being interrupted.
\i[element-neutral]\c[3]Hex Barrier\c[0] is another combat art that can help prevent you from getting interrupted while trying to use consumables or combat arts with long startup times.
Tip: If you hit an enemy with \i[element-shock]\c[3]Stasis Rune\c[0], they will have very high defense while stunned.
Use this window of opportunity to activate slow guard arts or to use consumables!
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Shock Surge\c[0] grants both complete immunity and intangibility against attacks that are otherwise not guardable.
Other dash arts do not have this level of protection. Use it to get yourself out of sticky situations!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Ether Singularity\c[0] will slow you down while it is active. Be careful with this combat art if you are in a situation where agility is required!
Tip: \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Curse of Vanishing\c[0] can put an enemy out of the fight for a while, even though they still do reduced damage.
Depending on your stats, they might not even interrupt you with their attacks while debuffed.
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Lightning Hex\c[0] can be hard to aim, but it's easier if you stand directly on top of it while it charges.
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Lightning Hex\c[0] will charge up faster if you start to charge another combat art while it is still charging itself.
This is technically an exploit, but I'll mention it anyway.

Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Thunder Jacket\c[0] is best used when an enemy or boss is not currently vulnerable, so you can pay it off later when they are broken without needing to waste time casting it then.
Tip: With \i[element-shock]\c[3]Thunder Jacket\c[0] active, it will trigger even if you use dash arts to charge into an enemy.
It's quite satisfying to snipe enemies with \i[element-shock]\c[3]Shock Surge\c[0] while having a \i[element-shock]\c[3]Thunder Jacket\c[0] active!
Tip: Combat arts like \i[element-shock]\c[3]Shock Surge\c[0] have \c[1]red\c[0] names. This means the combat art causes damage to the user.
Likewise, combart arts such as \i[element-wave]\c[3]Essence Steal\c[0] have \c[2]green\c[0] names. These heal the user.
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Toxic Mire\c[0] slows down enemies inside it. This can be useful for lining up fast enemies for multi-hit attacks like \i[element-wave]\c[3]Beam Blaster\c[0].
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Wave Recall\c[0] can have many uses outside of combat too. You can even put the card on top of moving platforms, pushable crates, and other puzzle elements.
Keep in mind that CrossWorlds was not designed with this ability in mind!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Wave Recall\c[0] grants damage immunity during the teleport. Even with poor positioning and with an unsafe destination, it provides brief window of safety.
Tip: A good habit is to place down a \i[element-wave]\c[3]Wave Recall\c[0] card at the start of every battle.
You never know when you might need an instant teleport out of a dangerous situation!
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Throttle Hex\c[0] not only slows an enemy's flow of time, but also that of any complex projectiles they might have.
This can be used to slow a boss during a tough bullet pattern, making the projectiles slightly slower and thus easier to dodge.

Tip: If your \i[element-wave]\c[3]Heal Card\c[0] keeps getting shot down by enemies, \i[element-cold]\c[3]Brittle Barrier\c[0] is just wide enough to cover it for protection against enemy projectiles.
Tip: If you try to use \i[element-shock]\c[3]Stasis Rune\c[0] while it is on cooldown, you will get refunded \c[3]2 SP\c[0].

Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Heal Card\c[0] has diminishing returns! There is a \c[3]25%\c[0] chance each time you use it for the total healing count to decrease by \c[3]1\c[0]. It starts out at \c[3]15\c[0] heals but won't fall below \c[3]5\c[0].
If you turn on the combat art names in the UI settings, you can see the current heal count of this art.
It always resets to \c[3]15\c[0] when entering a new map or dying. Also, this diminishing return mechanic is shared among Heal Cards you cast on yourself and on your allies!
Tip: If you can pin an enemy with \i[element-cold]\c[3]Crystal Carnage\c[0], it's a perfect opportunity to follow up before the enemy is released from the stun lock!
Tip: \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Shining Shield\c[0] provides a full second of guaranteed perfect guards. Use this to brace for attacks or absorb projectiles!
Unlike the \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Guard Sphere\c[0] Spheromancer art, this will work regardless of your defense stats.
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Ray of G'oni\c[0] is not affected by gravity. The laser blast can travel across pits and gaps, and is able to damage enemies up to 1 elevation level below the blast.
This is notable because most other hitboxes in Crossworlds are not able to hit below themselves.
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Temporal Miasma\c[0]'s timeflow buff makes all your actions 50% faster while inside the zone.
This includes movement, combat arts, consuming items, and attacks!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Temporal Miasma\c[0] will apply a timeflow debuff to all enemies inside the zone.
Just like with \i[element-shock]\c[3]Throttle Hex\c[0], this debuff stacks with the \c[3]chill\c[0] status effect!
Tip: Immediately after using \i[element-shock]\c[3]Magnet Card\c[0], you can use \i[element-wave]\c[3]Wave Recall\c[0] to greatly extend its travel distance.
Tip: All Hexacast \i[element-heat]\c[3]Heat\c[0] arts become a more powerful version while \i[element-heat]\c[3]Shadowflame Sorcery\c[0] is active!
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Stasis Storm\c[0] doesn't have a cooldown mechanic like \i[element-shock]\c[3]Stasis Rune\c[0].
Nor does it grant any stat bonuses to enemies caught by it.
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Stasis Storm\c[0] deals the most damage closer to the center of its radius, since all lightning bolts pass through it.
Tip: \i[class-hexa]\c[3]Hexacast\c[0] characters can either have straight or homing charged shots by default.
Straight shots have a normal damage value of \c[3]1.3\c[0] but homing shots have a value of \c[3]1.0\c[0]. There is always a tradeoff!
Tip: \i[element-heat]\c[3]Kindling Dance\c[0] does low damage to single targets but it can really add up when used in the middle of a group of enemies!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Heal Battery\c[0] can also be utilized by party members or other allies that walk into its range!
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Lightning Hex\c[0] activates slow-motion during its aiming phase that affects everyone except the caster.
Charging a combat art will cancel out the slow-motion, so use this time to shoot a bunch of VRPs while everything else is still slowed!
Tip: \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Ruinous Pulse\c[0] can offset the DEF stat granted to enemies by \i[element-shock]\c[3]Stasis Rune\c[0].
Combine these to create a powerful window of attack!
Tip: \i[element-cold]\c[3]Icicle Lance\c[0] or \i[element-cold]\c[3]Lateral Sublimation\c[0] won't work if there is no room or if you try to use them directly into a wall.
If this happens, your \c[3]SP\c[0] will get refunded!
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Throttle Hex\c[0] can be used to debuff many different enemies all at once, but you can't stack it multiple times on the same enemy.
Using it again on an enemy that already has the debuff will only refresh the duration instead of stacking.
Tip: Unlike other classes, Hexacast \c[3]uncharged default shots\c[0] (\i[hexa-vrp] \i[hexa-vrp] \i[hexa-vrp]) will inflict status conditions!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Furious Dissonance\c[0]'s final projectile becomes more powerful if both clones get absorbed into the final spell card.
Each clone that is killed before the end of the combat art will reduce the power of the final blast!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Furious Dissonance\c[0]'s clones will automatically aim at any enemy targets you have hit yourself.
If no targets are available, they will match your aiming angle instead.
Welcome!\. Here you can find helpful \i[class-tri]\c[3]Triblader\c[0] tips.
Tip: \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Azure Charge\c[0] might not be powerful as an attack, but it can provide excellent mobility for dodging purposes.
It's also one of the fastest ways to travel, especially when combined with \i[element-shock]\c[3]Overclock\c[0].

Tip: Depending on your stats, the defense buff from \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Deploy Shields\c[0] or \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Blade Aura\c[0] might be enough for certain enemy attacks to no longer interrupt your actions.
This is a good opportunity to use arts with slow startup times like \i[element-heat]\c[3]Blade of E'nel\c[0].
Tip: \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Scattering Shards\c[0] is actually really effective in PVP duels.
Not for damage, but it confuses the opponent and makes it hard for them to approach.
Tip: You can have up to two \i[element-shock]\c[3]Magnet Prism\c[0] projectiles active at a time.
Tip: If you miss your \i[element-shock]\c[3]Targeted Surge\c[0] shot, you can quickly try again.
If you hit it again before the first attempt's prisms disappear, then they will all activate to shoot your target from the second attempt!
Tip: \i[element-cold]\c[3]Ice Brace\c[0] and \i[element-cold]\c[3]Stasis Stance\c[0] will not grant any protection from status effects.
Tip: \i[element-shock]\c[3]Overclock\c[0] will also increase the consumption speed of consumable items!
Tip: While \i[element-shock]\c[3]Overclock\c[0] increases your timeflow, it does not increase your jumping distance.
Tip: Even though \i[element-shock]\c[3]Overclock\c[0] debuffs your ATK and FOC stats, it has a lot of other utility value.
The increased timeflow makes dodging and reacting faster, and also speeds up combat arts that are otherwise slow and risky!

Tip: As with all ATK buffs, \i[element-heat]\c[3]Burning Sacrifice\c[0] will increase the damage of any projectiles you already have active at the time, such enemies currently suffering from \i[element-heat]\c[3]Daybreak\c[0].
The period before your \i[element-wave]\c[3]Verdant Infection\c[0] explodes is a great time to use it!
Tip: \i[element-cold]\c[3]Ice Flak\c[0] can be useful for hitting enemies with frontal shields that are weak from behind.
Tip: \i[element-cold]\c[3]Frozen Rays\c[0] will travel through solid walls. Use this to hit enemies that might otherwise be unreachable!
Tip: Charging any combat art will immediately cancel the time freeze from \i[element-shock]\c[3]Glitch Time\c[0]. Be careful about this!
Tip: There is a brief window where \i[element-wave]\c[3]Vortex Thrust\c[0] is dash-cancelable before the final swing.
Tip: You can have two \i[element-wave]\c[3]Vitality Spring\c[0] projectiles active at a time. Use this to cover a huge area, or to stack them for double the effect!
Tip: You can have two \i[element-wave]\c[3]Arcing Fae\c[0] projectiles active at a time. If you stagger the timing, this can create a relentless bombardment!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]So'najiz Phalanx\c[0] won't spawn decoys if there is not adequate room to your left and right. Less decoys means less damage, so try to use this in open terrain!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Spectral Legion\c[0] decoys are fragile and can be destroyed easily. Be careful about spawning them when the battlefield is not currently safe!
Tip: \i[element-wave]\c[3]Phase Jump\c[0] is a very powerful dodge tool when used with good timing. Jump right over powerful attacks from bosses!
Tip: If you need a window of safety to use consumables or activate interruptible combat arts, \i[element-wave]\c[3]Soul Shatter\c[0] can provide much-needed crowd control.

Tip: Unlike the Spheromancer \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Guard Sphere\c[0] art, the \i[element-cold]\c[3]Ice Brace\c[0], \i[element-cold]\c[3]Stasis Stance\c[0], and \i[element-cold]\c[3]Tower of Tranquility\c[0] arts will work regardless of your defense stats and modifiers.
It can be a good way to block attacks if you are otherwise running a glass cannon build!
Tip: \i[element-cold]\c[3]Tower of Tranquility\c[0] can be canceled early by using a consumable.
Tip: Clones from \i[element-wave]\c[3]Spectral Swordsman\c[0] and \i[element-wave]\c[3]Spectral Legion\c[0] benefit from your \c[3]assault\c[0] modifier when performing melee attacks!

Tip: \i[element-neutral]\c[3]Guard Sphere\c[0] is lame!\! (Yep, this is real official information).
Tip: \i[element-heat]\c[3]Ancient Sun\c[0] is really bad!\! (That's the whole tip).
Tip: \i[element-heat]\c[3]Recoil Trumpet\c[0] and similar counter arts can perfect guard ranged attacks the entire time they are up.
You can combine this with the \c[3]avenger\c[0] modifier for a lot of free \c[3]SP\c[0] even without needing high defensive stats.

It's pretty fun to go into the official areas and pretend to be a basic NPC.
Especially when clueless players walk right past you.
You can download it on the mod browser if you want to give it a try!
